Many packages (got, chalk v5, node-fetch v3, execa, etc.) are now ESM-only. If your project uses CJS (`"type": "commonjs"` or no type field), you cannot `require()` them.

```typescript
// Option 1: Switch your project to ESM
// package.json: { "type": "module" }
// tsconfig.json: { "module": "node16", "moduleResolution": "node16" }

// Option 2: Dynamic import() from CJS
async function main() {
  const { got } = await import('got');
  const data = await got('https://api.example.com').json();
}

// Option 3: Use the CJS-compatible version
// npm install got@11  (last CJS version)
// npm install chalk@4
// npm install node-fetch@2

// Option 4: Use a bundler (tsup, esbuild) that handles interop
// tsup src/index.ts --format cjs
// The bundler inlines the ESM code and wraps it
```

This is the #1 Node.js ecosystem pain point. When starting new projects, use `"type": "module"` to avoid it entirely.

Setting `"type": "module"` in package.json switches ALL `.js` files in that package to ESM. This has cascading effects.

```jsonc
// package.json
{
  "type": "module"
}
```

What changes:
```typescript
// 1. import/export syntax is native (no transpilation needed)
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises'; // works
const fs = require('fs'); // SyntaxError: require is not defined in ES module

// 2. __dirname and __filename don't exist
// BAD:
console.log(__dirname); // ReferenceError

// GOOD:
import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url';
import { dirname } from 'node:path';
const __filename = fileURLToPath(import.meta.url);
const __dirname = dirname(__filename);

// Node 21.2+ shortcut:
const __dirname = import.meta.dirname; // built-in!
const __filename = import.meta.filename;

// 3. .cjs extension forces CommonJS for specific files
// jest.config.cjs — Jest may need CJS config
// .eslintrc.cjs — ESLint flat config prefers .mjs but classic needs .cjs

// 4. JSON imports need assertion
import pkg from './package.json' with { type: 'json' };
```

If you need both ESM and CJS files in the same package, use `.mjs`/`.cjs` extensions explicitly.

To support both ESM and CJS consumers, use conditional exports in package.json with separate entry points.

```jsonc
// package.json
{
  "name": "my-lib",
  "type": "module",
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "import": {
        "types": "./dist/index.d.ts",
        "default": "./dist/index.js"
      },
      "require": {
        "types": "./dist/index.d.cts",
        "default": "./dist/index.cjs"
      }
    },
    "./utils": {
      "import": "./dist/utils.js",
      "require": "./dist/utils.cjs"
    }
  },
  "main": "./dist/index.cjs",
  "module": "./dist/index.js",
  "types": "./dist/index.d.ts",
  "files": ["dist"]
}
```

```typescript
// tsup.config.ts — builds both formats
import { defineConfig } from 'tsup';
export default defineConfig({
  entry: ['src/index.ts', 'src/utils.ts'],
  format: ['esm', 'cjs'],
  dts: true,
  splitting: false,
  clean: true,
});
```

Order matters in `exports`: put `types` first, then `import`/`require`. Always include `main` and `types` as fallbacks for older tools. Test with both `import('my-lib')` and `require('my-lib')` before publishing.

In ESM modules, `__dirname` and `__filename` are not available. There are two approaches depending on your Node version.

```typescript
// Node < 21.2 — manual construction
import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url';
import { dirname, join } from 'node:path';

const __filename = fileURLToPath(import.meta.url);
const __dirname = dirname(__filename);
const configPath = join(__dirname, '..', 'config', 'default.json');

// Node >= 21.2 — built-in
const dir = import.meta.dirname;       // same as __dirname
const file = import.meta.filename;     // same as __filename
const configPath2 = join(import.meta.dirname, '..', 'config', 'default.json');

// For URL-based resolution (works everywhere)
const configUrl = new URL('../config/default.json', import.meta.url);
// Use with fs:
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
const content = await readFile(configUrl, 'utf-8');
```

The `new URL(relative, import.meta.url)` pattern is the most portable — it works in Node, Deno, and browsers. Use `import.meta.dirname` when you need a plain string path and target Node 21.2+.

tsup wraps esbuild for zero-config TypeScript building with .d.ts generation. Here's a production config.

```typescript
// tsup.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'tsup';

export default defineConfig({
  entry: ['src/index.ts'],
  format: ['esm', 'cjs'],
  dts: true,             // Generate declaration files
  splitting: false,      // No code splitting for libraries
  sourcemap: true,
  clean: true,           // Clean dist/ before build
  target: 'node18',
  outDir: 'dist',
  treeshake: true,
  minify: false,         // Don't minify libraries
  external: ['zod'],     // Don't bundle peer deps

  // Banner for ESM/CJS interop shim
  banner: ({ format }) => {
    if (format === 'esm') return {};
    return {
      js: `const require = (await import('node:module')).createRequire(import.meta.url);`,
    };
  },
});
```

```bash
# Build
npx tsup

# Watch mode
npx tsup --watch

# Override entry from CLI
npx tsup src/cli.ts --format esm --target node20
```

tsup is the best choice for libraries. For apps, use tsc or your framework's bundler. Key: always set `external` for peer dependencies to avoid bundling them.

Vite's library mode builds packages with Rollup under the hood, producing optimized ESM and CJS bundles.

```typescript
// vite.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import { resolve } from 'path';
import dts from 'vite-plugin-dts';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    dts({ rollupTypes: true }), // Bundle .d.ts into single file
  ],
  build: {
    lib: {
      entry: resolve(__dirname, 'src/index.ts'),
      name: 'MyLib',
      formats: ['es', 'cjs'],
      fileName: (format) => `index.${format === 'es' ? 'js' : 'cjs'}`,
    },
    rollupOptions: {
      external: ['react', 'react-dom'], // Peer deps
      output: {
        globals: { react: 'React', 'react-dom': 'ReactDOM' },
      },
    },
    sourcemap: true,
    minify: false,
  },
});
```

When to use Vite library mode vs tsup: Vite is better for libraries with CSS, assets, or React components (handles CSS modules, SVG imports). tsup is better for pure TypeScript/Node libraries (simpler config, faster builds). Both produce dual ESM/CJS output.

esbuild compiles TypeScript 10-100x faster than tsc but does NOT type-check. Use it for builds, use tsc for checking.

```typescript
// build.ts — programmatic API
import * as esbuild from 'esbuild';

await esbuild.build({
  entryPoints: ['src/index.ts'],
  bundle: true,
  outfile: 'dist/index.js',
  platform: 'node',
  target: 'node18',
  format: 'esm',
  sourcemap: true,
  external: ['pg-native'],  // Native modules
  define: {
    'process.env.NODE_ENV': '"production"',
  },
  banner: {
    js: '#!/usr/bin/env node', // For CLI tools
  },
});
```

```bash
# CLI usage
esbuild src/index.ts --bundle --platform=node --outfile=dist/index.js

# Watch mode
esbuild src/index.ts --bundle --outfile=dist/index.js --watch

# CI script — typecheck + build in parallel
tsc --noEmit & esbuild src/index.ts --bundle --outfile=dist/index.js & wait
