Passing a method as a callback loses its `this` context. This is one of the most common JavaScript bugs.

```typescript
class UserService {
  private users = new Map<string, string>();

  addUser(id: string, name: string) {
    this.users.set(id, name); // 'this' must be UserService
  }

  // BAD — 'this' is lost when passed as callback
  registerRoutes(app: Express) {
    app.post('/users', this.addUser); // 'this' is undefined!
  }

  // FIX 1: Arrow function (lexical this)
  addUserArrow = (id: string, name: string) => {
    this.users.set(id, name); // always correct
  };

  // FIX 2: Bind in constructor
  constructor() {
    this.addUser = this.addUser.bind(this);
  }

  // FIX 3: Wrapper arrow in the callback
  registerRoutesFixed(app: Express) {
    app.post('/users', (id, name) => this.addUser(id, name));
  }
}

// Also affects: setTimeout, Array methods, event handlers
class Timer {
  count = 0;
  // BAD: setTimeout(this.tick, 1000)
  // GOOD:
  tick = () => { this.count++; };
  start() { setInterval(this.tick, 1000); }
}
```

The arrow function property pattern (Fix 1) is cleanest but creates a new function per instance. Use `.bind()` in the constructor for shared prototype methods.

Closures capture variables by reference, not by value. In loops, this means all closures share the same variable.

```typescript
// BAD — all callbacks log 5
for (var i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // 5, 5, 5, 5, 5
}

// FIX 1: Use let (block-scoped)
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
}

// The tricky version that STILL bites with let:
const fns: (() => void)[] = [];
let prefix = 'A';
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  fns.push(() => console.log(prefix, i));
}
prefix = 'B';
fns.forEach(fn => fn()); // 'B' 0, 'B' 1, 'B' 2 — prefix is NOT block-scoped!

// FIX: capture the value explicitly
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  const capturedPrefix = prefix;
  fns.push(() => console.log(capturedPrefix, i));
}

// Async version of the same bug:
const urls = ['/a', '/b', '/c'];
for (const url of urls) {
  // SAFE: for-of with const creates new binding per iteration
  fetch(url).then(res => console.log(url, res.status));
}
```

Rule: always use `const` or `let` in loops. If you capture a mutable outer variable, assign it to a const inside the loop body first.

A single long synchronous operation blocks the entire Node.js event loop, freezing all connections. Even 50ms of blocking is visible.

```typescript
// DETECTION: monitor event loop delay
import { monitorEventLoopDelay } from 'node:perf_hooks';

const h = monitorEventLoopDelay({ resolution: 20 });
h.enable();

setInterval(() => {
  console.log(`Event loop delay p99: ${(h.percentile(99) / 1e6).toFixed(1)}ms`);
  h.reset();
}, 5000);

// COMMON BLOCKERS:

// 1. JSON.parse on large payloads
// BAD:
const data = JSON.parse(hugeString); // blocks for 100ms+
// FIX: Stream parse or move to worker thread

// 2. Synchronous file operations
// BAD:
const content = readFileSync('big-file.txt'); // blocks
// FIX:
const content2 = await readFile('big-file.txt'); // non-blocking

// 3. Regex catastrophic backtracking
// BAD:
'a'.repeat(30).match(/(a+)+b/); // hangs for seconds
// FIX: Use linear-time regex or RE2:
import RE2 from 're2';
const safe = new RE2('(a+)+b');

// 4. Crypto operations
// BAD: crypto.pbkdf2Sync()
// FIX: await crypto.pbkdf2() — the async version uses libuv threads

// GENERAL FIX: offload to worker
import { Worker } from 'node:worker_threads';
function offload<T>(fn: () => T): Promise<T> {
  // Move CPU-bound work off the main thread
}
```

JSON.stringify throws on BigInt values. This crashes API responses and logging unexpectedly.

```typescript
// THE ERROR:
const data = { id: 1n, name: 'test' };
JSON.stringify(data);
// TypeError: Do not know how to serialize a BigInt

// FIX 1: Custom replacer
function bigIntReplacer(key: string, value: any) {
  return typeof value === 'bigint' ? value.toString() : value;
}
JSON.stringify(data, bigIntReplacer);
// {"id":"1","name":"test"}

// FIX 2: Transform before serialization
function sanitize<T>(obj: T): T {
  return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj, bigIntReplacer));
}

// FIX 3: Monkey-patch (use with caution)
(BigInt.prototype as any).toJSON = function () {
  return this.toString();
};

// WHERE THIS BITES:
// - PostgreSQL BIGINT columns return BigInt in some drivers
// - Prisma returns BigInt for Int8 columns
// - process.hrtime.bigint() for timing

// PRISMA SPECIFIC FIX:
// In schema.prisma, use @db.Integer instead of @db.BigInt
// Or transform in middleware:
prisma.$use(async (params, next) => {
  const result = await next(params);
  return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(result, bigIntReplacer));
});
```

This is especially insidious because it only fails at runtime when a BigInt value is actually present — tests with small IDs may not catch it.

