This error occurs when TypeScript infers a type from a dependency that isn't directly importable from your project's perspective. Common with monorepos and hoisted dependencies.

```typescript
// CAUSE: Function return type references an internal type from a dependency
import { createClient } from 'some-lib';
export const client = createClient(); // TS2742: inferred type can't be named

// FIX 1: Add explicit type annotation
import type { Client } from 'some-lib';
export const client: Client = createClient();

// FIX 2: Re-export with type
export type { Client } from 'some-lib';

// FIX 3: If the type isn't exported, use ReturnType
export const client: ReturnType<typeof createClient> = createClient();

// FIX 4: In monorepo — install the transitive dependency explicitly
// npm install some-lib-internal-types

// FIX 5: tsconfig — set declaration: false if you don't need .d.ts
{
  "compilerOptions": { "declaration": false }
}
```

This commonly appears when enabling `composite: true` for project references, which forces `declaration: true`.

When writing to Node.js Writable streams, you must handle backpressure — the signal that the consumer can't keep up with the producer.

```typescript
import { createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';

async function writeWithBackpressure(
  stream: NodeJS.WritableStream,
  items: string[]
): Promise<void> {
  for (const item of items) {
    const canContinue = stream.write(item + '\n');
    if (!canContinue) {
      // Buffer is full — wait for drain event
      await new Promise<void>((resolve) => stream.once('drain', resolve));
    }
  }
  // Signal end and wait for finish
  await new Promise<void>((resolve, reject) => {
    stream.end(() => resolve());
    stream.on('error', reject);
  });
}

// Usage
const ws = createWriteStream('output.txt');
const lines = Array.from({ length: 1_000_000 }, (_, i) => `Line ${i}`);
await writeWithBackpressure(ws, lines);

// Modern approach with pipeline:
import { Readable, pipeline } from 'node:stream';
import { promisify } from 'node:util';

const pipelineAsync = promisify(pipeline);
await pipelineAsync(
  Readable.from(lines.map(l => l + '\n')),
  createWriteStream('output2.txt')
);
```

Ignoring backpressure (not checking `.write()` return value) causes unbounded memory growth. The pipeline approach handles it automatically.

Graceful shutdown lets in-flight requests finish while rejecting new ones. Essential for zero-downtime deployments.

```typescript
import { createServer } from 'node:http';

const server = createServer(handler);
server.listen(3000);

const connections = new Set<import('node:net').Socket>();
server.on('connection', (conn) => {
  connections.add(conn);
  conn.on('close', () => connections.delete(conn));
});

async function shutdown(signal: string) {
  console.log(`${signal} received, starting graceful shutdown`);

  // Stop accepting new connections
  server.close(() => console.log('HTTP server closed'));

  // Close idle keep-alive connections
  for (const conn of connections) {
    conn.end();
  }

  // Close database pools
  await db.end();

  // Close Redis
  await redis.quit();

  // Force exit after timeout
  setTimeout(() => {
    console.error('Forced shutdown after timeout');
    process.exit(1);
  }, 10_000).unref();
}

process.on('SIGTERM', () => shutdown('SIGTERM'));
process.on('SIGINT', () => shutdown('SIGINT'));

// IMPORTANT: Docker sends SIGTERM, then SIGKILL after 10s
// Kubernetes sends SIGTERM, then SIGKILL after terminationGracePeriodSeconds
// Make sure your shutdown completes within that window
```

Always handle both SIGTERM (Docker/K8s) and SIGINT (Ctrl+C). Use `.unref()` on the force-exit timer so it doesn't keep the process alive.

The built-in `Partial<T>` only makes top-level properties optional. For deeply nested objects, you need a recursive version.

```typescript
type DeepPartial<T> = T extends object
  ? { [K in keyof T]?: DeepPartial<T[K]> }
  : T;

// Usage
interface Config {
  server: {
    host: string;
    port: number;
    ssl: {
      cert: string;
      key: string;
    };
  };
  database: {
    url: string;
    pool: { min: number; max: number };
  };
}

// Only override what you need
const overrides: DeepPartial<Config> = {
  server: { port: 8080 }, // host and ssl are optional
  // database entirely optional
};

// Deep merge function to apply overrides
function deepMerge<T extends object>(base: T, override: DeepPartial<T>): T {
  const result = { ...base };
  for (const key in override) {
    const val = override[key];
    if (val && typeof val === 'object' && !Array.isArray(val)) {
      (result as any)[key] = deepMerge((base as any)[key] ?? {}, val as any);
    } else if (val !== undefined) {
      (result as any)[key] = val;
    }
  }
  return result;
}

const config = deepMerge(defaultConfig, overrides);
```

Node.js EventEmitter is untyped by default. Create a typed wrapper for compile-time event name and payload checking.

```typescript
import { EventEmitter } from 'node:events';

type EventMap = Record<string, any[]>;

class TypedEmitter<Events extends EventMap> {
  private emitter = new EventEmitter();

  on<K extends keyof Events & string>(
    event: K,
    listener: (...args: Events[K]) => void
  ): this {
    this.emitter.on(event, listener as any);
    return this;
  }

  emit<K extends keyof Events & string>(
    event: K,
    ...args: Events[K]
  ): boolean {
    return this.emitter.emit(event, ...args);
  }

  off<K extends keyof Events & string>(
    event: K,
    listener: (...args: Events[K]) => void
  ): this {
    this.emitter.off(event, listener as any);
    return this;
  }
}

// Usage
interface AppEvents {
  'user:login': [userId: string, timestamp: Date];
  'user:logout': [userId: string];
  'error': [error: Error];
}

const bus = new TypedEmitter<AppEvents>();
bus.on('user:login', (userId, timestamp) => { /* both typed */ });
bus.emit('user:login', 'u123', new Date()); // OK
bus.emit('user:login', 123);  // Error: number not assignable to string
bus.emit('typo');              // Error: 'typo' not in AppEvents
```

TypeScript enums have surprising behaviors that trip up developers. Union types are simpler and more predictable.

```typescript
// PITFALL 1: Numeric enums allow any number
enum Status { Active, Inactive }
const s: Status = 999; // No error! TypeScript allows this.

// PITFALL 2: Enums are nominal — same shape doesn't match
enum Color { Red, Green }
enum Priority { High, Low }
const c: Color = Priority.High; // Error even though both are 0

// PITFALL 3: Enums generate runtime code
enum Dir { Up, Down } // Compiles to IIFE with reverse mapping
// Adds ~100 bytes per enum to bundle

// PITFALL 4: const enum + isolatedModules = trouble
const enum Fruit { Apple, Banana } // Inlined at compile time
// But with isolatedModules (required by esbuild/Vite), const enums
// from external modules can't be inlined → runtime error

// BETTER: Use union types
type Status2 = 'active' | 'inactive';
type Direction = 'up' | 'down' | 'left' | 'right';

// If you need a mapping object:
const STATUS = { Active: 'active', Inactive: 'inactive' } as const;
type StatusValue = typeof STATUS[keyof typeof STATUS]; // 'active' | 'inactive'

// Benefits:
// - No runtime code generated
// - Works with isolatedModules
// - Proper exhaustiveness checking
// - String values show in debugger/logs
```

Function overloads let you define multiple call signatures for a single function. The implementation signature must be compatible with all overloads.

```typescript
// Overloaded function
function fetch(url: string): Promise<Response>;
function fetch(url: string, options: RequestInit): Promise<Response>;
function fetch(urls: string[]): Promise<Response[]>;
function fetch(
  input: string | string[],
  options?: RequestInit
): Promise<Response | Response[]> {
  if (Array.isArray(input)) {
    return Promise.all(input.map(url => globalThis.fetch(url)));
  }
  return globalThis.fetch(input, options);
}

// Better alternative: conditional return types
function getValue<T extends boolean>(
  key: string,
  required: T
): T extends true ? string : string | undefined {
  const val = process.env[key];
  if (required && !val) throw new Error(`Missing ${key}`);
  return val as any;
}

const must = getValue('API_KEY', true);   // string
const maybe = getValue('DEBUG', false);    // string | undefined

// Generic overloads for precise return types
function parse(input: string, format: 'json'): object;
function parse(input: string, format: 'csv'): string[][];
function parse(input: string, format: 'json' | 'csv') {
  return format === 'json' ? JSON.parse(input) : csvParse(input);
}
```

`.pipe()` and `stream.pipeline()` both connect streams, but their error handling is fundamentally different.

```typescript
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
import { createGzip } from 'node:zlib';

// BAD: .pipe() does NOT propagate errors
createReadStream('input.txt')
  .pipe(createGzip())
  .pipe(createWriteStream('output.gz'));
// If input.txt doesn't exist:
// - ReadStream emits 'error'
// - But the WriteStream is NEVER closed/cleaned up
// - The .gz file is left as a corrupt empty file
// - No error bubbles up to your code

// GOOD: pipeline() handles everything
try {
  await pipeline(
    createReadStream('input.txt'),
    createGzip(),
    createWriteStream('output.gz')
  );
  console.log('Done');
} catch (err) {
  // Error from ANY stream in the chain surfaces here
  // All streams are properly destroyed/cleaned up
  console.error('Pipeline failed:', err);
}

// With AbortController
const ac = new AbortController();
setTimeout(() => ac.abort(), 5000);

await pipeline(source, transform, dest, { signal: ac.signal });
```

Rule: NEVER use `.pipe()` in production code. Always use `pipeline()` from `node:stream/promises`. It automatically destroys all streams on error and supports AbortSignal for cancellation.

Instead of try/catch everywhere, encode success/failure in the type system. Functions return explicit Result types.

```typescript
type Result<T, E = Error> =
  | { success: true; data: T }
  | { success: false; error: E };

function ok<T>(data: T): Result<T, never> {
  return { success: true, data };
}

function err<E>(error: E): Result<never, E> {
  return { success: false, error };
}

// Domain errors as union
type ParseError = { code: 'INVALID_JSON'; raw: string }
  | { code: 'MISSING_FIELD'; field: string }
  | { code: 'INVALID_VALUE'; field: string; value: unknown };

function parseConfig(raw: string): Result<Config, ParseError> {
  let json: unknown;
  try {
    json = JSON.parse(raw);
  } catch {
    return err({ code: 'INVALID_JSON', raw });
  }
  if (typeof json !== 'object' || !json) {
    return err({ code: 'INVALID_JSON', raw });
  }
  if (!('port' in json)) {
    return err({ code: 'MISSING_FIELD', field: 'port' });
  }
  return ok(json as Config);
}

// Usage — compiler forces you to check
const result = parseConfig(input);
if (!result.success) {
  switch (result.error.code) {
    case 'INVALID_JSON': console.log('Bad JSON:', result.error.raw); break;
    case 'MISSING_FIELD': console.log('Missing:', result.error.field); break;
  }
  return;
}
console.log(result.data.port); // TypeScript knows this is Config
```

TypeScript's control flow narrowing works automatically with `typeof`, `instanceof`, and `in`. But sometimes you need custom type guards.

```typescript
// Built-in narrowing with 'in'
type Fish = { swim: () => void };
type Bird = { fly: () => void };

function move(animal: Fish | Bird) {
  if ('swim' in animal) {
    animal.swim(); // TypeScript knows it's Fish
  } else {
    animal.fly();  // TypeScript knows it's Bird
  }
}

// Custom type guard (user-defined)
function isFish(animal: Fish | Bird): animal is Fish {
  return 'swim' in animal;
}

// GOTCHA: type guards can lie!
function isString(val: unknown): val is string {
  return true; // TypeScript trusts this — no runtime check!
}
const x: unknown = 42;
if (isString(x)) {
  x.toUpperCase(); // Compiles fine, crashes at runtime!
}

// SAFE pattern: assert function (throws on failure)
function assertIsString(val: unknown): asserts val is string {
  if (typeof val !== 'string') {
    throw new TypeError(`Expected string, got ${typeof val}`);
  }
}

// Array filter with type guard
const mixed: (string | null)[] = ['a', null, 'b', null];
const strings: string[] = mixed.filter((s): s is string => s !== null);
// Without the type guard: filter returns (string | null)[]
```

Type guards are powerful but dangerous — TypeScript blindly trusts them. Always include a real runtime check.

Zod schemas validate runtime data and infer TypeScript types — eliminating the need to maintain types and validators separately.

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

// Define schema once, get both validation and type
const UserSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().uuid(),
  email: z.string().email(),
  name: z.string().min(1).max(100),
  role: z.enum(['admin', 'user', 'viewer']),
  metadata: z.record(z.string(), z.unknown()).optional(),
  createdAt: z.coerce.date(), // Accepts string/number, returns Date
});

type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;
// { id: string; email: string; name: string; role: 'admin'|'user'|'viewer'; ... }

// Partial schema for updates
const UpdateUserSchema = UserSchema.partial().omit({ id: true, createdAt: true });
type UpdateUser = z.infer<typeof UpdateUserSchema>;

// Transform and default
const QuerySchema = z.object({
  page: z.coerce.number().int().positive().default(1),
  limit: z.coerce.number().int().min(1).max(100).default(20),
  sort: z.enum(['asc', 'desc']).default('desc'),
  q: z.string().trim().optional().transform(s => s?.toLowerCase()),
});

// API handler usage
function handleRequest(rawBody: unknown) {
  const result = UserSchema.safeParse(rawBody);
  if (!result.success) {
    return { status: 400, errors: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }
  return { status: 200, user: result.data };
}
```

When `isolatedModules: true` (required by esbuild, Vite, swc, tsx), certain TypeScript features break because the transpiler processes files individually.

```typescript
// tsconfig.json: { "compilerOptions": { "isolatedModules": true } }

// BROKEN 1: const enum from another file
// types.ts
export const enum Color { Red, Green, Blue }
// app.ts
import { Color } from './types';
console.log(Color.Red); // Error: cannot access ambient const enums
// FIX: Remove 'const' keyword, or inline the values

// BROKEN 2: Re-exporting types without 'type' keyword
export { MyType } from './types'; // Error with isolatedModules
export type { MyType } from './types'; // FIX: add 'type'

// BROKEN 3: Namespace merging across files
// file1.ts
namespace Utils { export function a() {} }
// file2.ts
namespace Utils { export function b() {} } // Can't merge across files
// FIX: Use modules instead of namespaces

// BROKEN 4: Files without imports/exports
const x = 1; // Error: file is not a module
export {}; // FIX: add empty export
```

Set `isolatedModules: true` from the start of any project. It catches patterns that are incompatible with modern build tools. Virtually all modern tools (Vite, Next.js, esbuild, swc) require it.

Generic constraints restrict what types can be passed to a generic function, enabling safe property access on generic parameters.

```typescript
// Basic constraint
function getLength<T extends { length: number }>(item: T): number {
  return item.length; // Safe: T guaranteed to have .length
}
getLength('hello');     // OK: string has length
getLength([1, 2, 3]);   // OK: array has length
getLength(42);          // Error: number has no length

// keyof constraint for property access
function getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}
const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 30 };
const name = getProperty(user, 'name'); // string
const age = getProperty(user, 'age');   // number
getProperty(user, 'email');             // Error: 'email' not in keyof

// Multiple constraints with intersection
function merge<T extends object, U extends object>(a: T, b: U): T & U {
  return { ...a, ...b };
}

// Constraint with conditional default
function createStore<T extends Record<string, unknown> = Record<string, never>>(
  initial?: T
) {
  const state: T = initial ?? ({} as T);
  return {
    get: <K extends keyof T>(key: K): T[K] => state[key],
    set: <K extends keyof T>(key: K, value: T[K]) => { state[key] = value; },
  };
}

const store = createStore({ count: 0, name: 'test' });
store.get('count'); // number
store.set('name', 'updated'); // OK
store.set('name', 123); // Error
```

JSON.parse returns `any`, which defeats TypeScript's type system. Here are safe patterns to handle parsed JSON.

```typescript
// UNSAFE — any spreads through your code
const data = JSON.parse(rawString); // any
data.whatever.you.want; // No error, but will crash

// PATTERN 1: Parse then validate with Zod
import { z } from 'zod';
const schema = z.object({ name: z.string(), age: z.number() });
const data1 = schema.parse(JSON.parse(rawString));
// data1 is { name: string; age: number } — validated

// PATTERN 2: Type assertion with unknown intermediate
const raw: unknown = JSON.parse(rawString);
if (typeof raw === 'object' && raw !== null && 'name' in raw) {
  const data2 = raw as { name: string };
}

// PATTERN 3: Generic wrapper function
function parseJSON<T>(text: string, validator: (v: unknown) => v is T): T {
  const parsed: unknown = JSON.parse(text);
  if (!validator(parsed)) {
    throw new Error('JSON validation failed');
  }
  return parsed;
}

// PATTERN 4: Safe parse that returns Result
function safeParseJSON(text: string): { ok: true; data: unknown } | { ok: false; error: Error } {
  try {
    return { ok: true, data: JSON.parse(text) };
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: e instanceof Error ? e : new Error(String(e)) };
  }
}

const result = safeParseJSON(input);
if (result.ok) {
  // result.data is unknown — must narrow before use
}
```

Best practice: JSON.parse should always be immediately followed by validation. Never pass `any` from JSON.parse into typed functions.

Node 18+ includes Web Streams API (ReadableStream, WritableStream, TransformStream) alongside the classic node:stream API.

```typescript
// Converting between Node streams and Web streams
import { Readable } from 'node:stream';

// Node Readable → Web ReadableStream
const nodeStream = Readable.from(['hello', ' ', 'world']);
const webStream = Readable.toWeb(nodeStream);

// Web ReadableStream → Node Readable
const backToNode = Readable.fromWeb(webStream);

// Using Web TransformStream for text processing
const uppercase = new TransformStream({
  transform(chunk, controller) {
    controller.enqueue(chunk.toString().toUpperCase());
  }
});

// Piping Web streams
const source = new ReadableStream({
  start(controller) {
    controller.enqueue('hello ');
    controller.enqueue('world');
    controller.close();
  }
});

const result = source.pipeThrough(uppercase);
const reader = result.getReader();
while (true) {
  const { done, value } = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  console.log(value); // 'HELLO ', 'WORLD'
}

// Fetch response body is a Web ReadableStream
const res = await fetch('https://example.com/large-file');
for await (const chunk of res.body!) {
  process.stdout.write(chunk);
}
```

Use Web Streams for code that needs to run in both Node.js and browsers. Use Node streams (node:stream) for Node-only code — they have richer APIs and better ecosystem support.

Express types are tricky. Here's how to properly type handlers, middleware, and request extensions.

```typescript
import type { Request, Response, NextFunction, RequestHandler } from 'express';

// Basic typed handler
interface CreateUserBody { name: string; email: string; }
interface CreateUserResponse { id: string; name: string; }

const createUser: RequestHandler<
  {},                    // Params
  CreateUserResponse,    // ResBody
  CreateUserBody,        // ReqBody
  {}                     // Query
> = async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body; // typed!
  res.json({ id: '123', name });    // typed!
};

// Extending Request with custom properties
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      userId?: string;
      role?: 'admin' | 'user';
    }
  }
}

// Auth middleware
const auth: RequestHandler = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) { res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }); return; }
  const payload = verifyToken(token);
  req.userId = payload.sub;  // Typed via global augmentation
  req.role = payload.role;
  next();
};

// Error handler (4 params)
const errorHandler = (
  err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, _next: NextFunction
) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
};
```

Key: Express error handlers MUST have exactly 4 parameters. Express identifies error handlers by the parameter count.

Process items concurrently but with a limit on simultaneous operations. Useful for API calls, file processing, and batch jobs.

```typescript
async function parallelLimit<T, R>(
  items: T[],
  limit: number,
  fn: (item: T, index: number) => Promise<R>
): Promise<R[]> {
  const results: R[] = new Array(items.length);
  let nextIndex = 0;

  async function worker() {
    while (nextIndex < items.length) {
      const index = nextIndex++;
      results[index] = await fn(items[index], index);
    }
  }

  const workers = Array.from(
    { length: Math.min(limit, items.length) },
    () => worker()
  );
  await Promise.all(workers);
  return results;
}

// Usage: process 1000 URLs, 10 at a time
const urls = Array.from({ length: 1000 }, (_, i) => `https://api.example.com/item/${i}`);

const results = await parallelLimit(urls, 10, async (url, i) => {
  const res = await fetch(url);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`${url}: ${res.status}`);
  console.log(`Completed ${i + 1}/${urls.length}`);
  return res.json();
});

// With p-limit (smaller, battle-tested)
import pLimit from 'p-limit';
const limit = pLimit(10);
const results2 = await Promise.all(
  urls.map(url => limit(() => fetch(url).then(r => r.json())))
);
```

