Record, index signatures, and Map serve different purposes for key-value data. Choose based on key constraints.

```typescript
// Record<K, V> — fixed set of known keys
type Permissions = Record<'read' | 'write' | 'delete', boolean>;
const perms: Permissions = { read: true, write: false, delete: false };
// perms.execute → Error: not in 'read' | 'write' | 'delete'

// Index signature — open-ended string/number keys
interface Cache {
  [key: string]: Buffer | undefined; // Must include undefined
}
const cache: Cache = {};
cache['anything'] = Buffer.from('data'); // OK
const val = cache['key']; // Buffer | undefined

// Record<string, V> vs index signature
// Record<string, V> forces ALL string keys to have value V
// Index signature allows missing keys (returns undefined with noUncheckedIndexedAccess)

// BEST: Enable noUncheckedIndexedAccess in tsconfig
// { "compilerOptions": { "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true } }
const obj: Record<string, number> = { a: 1 };
obj['a']; // number | undefined (with the flag)
obj['a']; // number (without the flag — UNSAFE)

// When keys are dynamic: use Map
const sessions = new Map<string, { userId: string; expiresAt: Date }>();
sessions.set(token, { userId: 'u1', expiresAt: new Date() });
const session = sessions.get(token); // { userId, expiresAt } | undefined
// Map advantages: O(1) delete, size property, no prototype pollution
```

Enabling `strictNullChecks` on a large codebase produces hundreds of errors. Here's the incremental migration strategy.

```jsonc
// Step 1: Enable in tsconfig, add to specific files first
// tsconfig.json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": false,
    "strictNullChecks": true  // Enable just this one
  }
}
```

```typescript
// Step 2: Fix the most common patterns

// Pattern A: Optional chaining
// Before: user.address.street (crashes if address is null)
// After:
const street = user.address?.street;

// Pattern B: Nullish coalescing
const port = config.port ?? 3000; // 0 is preserved (unlike ||)

// Pattern C: Non-null assertion (use sparingly)
const el = document.getElementById('root')!; // You KNOW it exists

// Pattern D: Type guard for arrays
const item = array.find(x => x.id === targetId);
if (!item) throw new Error(`Item ${targetId} not found`);
// item is now narrowed to non-null

// Pattern E: Map.get() returns T | undefined
const cache = new Map<string, User>();
const user = cache.get(key);
if (user) {
  console.log(user.name); // User, not User | undefined
}

// Step 3: For massive codebases, use ts-strictify
// npx ts-strictify  — adds @ts-strict-ignore to non-compliant files
// Migrate file by file, removing the comment as you fix each one
```

Golden rule: fix errors by adding proper null checks, not by adding `!` everywhere. Non-null assertions hide bugs.

pino is the fastest Node.js logger. It outputs structured JSON that log aggregators (Datadog, ELK, Loki) can parse and query.

```typescript
import pino from 'pino';

const logger = pino({
  level: process.env.LOG_LEVEL ?? 'info',
  transport: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development'
    ? { target: 'pino-pretty', options: { colorize: true } }
    : undefined, // JSON in production
  formatters: {
    level: (label) => ({ level: label }), // 'info' not 30
  },
  redact: ['req.headers.authorization', 'password', 'secret'],
});

// Child loggers carry context
const reqLogger = logger.child({ requestId: crypto.randomUUID() });
reqLogger.info({ userId: 'u123' }, 'Processing request');
// Output: {"level":"info","requestId":"abc","userId":"u123","msg":"Processing request"}

// Error logging — pass error as first arg
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch (err) {
  logger.error({ err }, 'Operation failed');
  // Serializes stack trace, message, and code
}

// Express/Fastify integration
import { randomUUID } from 'node:crypto';

function requestLogger(req, res, next) {
  req.log = logger.child({ requestId: randomUUID(), method: req.method, url: req.url });
  req.log.info('Request started');
  const start = Date.now();
  res.on('finish', () => {
    req.log.info({ status: res.statusCode, duration: Date.now() - start }, 'Request completed');
  });
  next();
}
```

When you install a package that doesn't include TypeScript types, you get `Could not find a declaration file for module 'xyz'`.

```bash
# Step 1: Check DefinitelyTyped for community types
npm install -D @types/express @types/lodash

# Step 2: If @types doesn't exist, create a declaration file
```

```typescript
// src/types/untyped-lib.d.ts
declare module 'untyped-lib' {
  // Minimal typing
  export function doSomething(input: string): Promise<string>;
  export interface Config {
    apiKey: string;
    timeout?: number;
  }
  export default function init(config: Config): void;
}

// Quick escape hatch — type everything as any
declare module 'another-untyped-lib';
// Now: import x from 'another-untyped-lib' works, but x is any

// For modules with subpath imports
declare module 'some-lib/utils' {
  export function helper(): void;
}
```

```jsonc
// tsconfig.json — tell TypeScript where to find declarations
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "typeRoots": ["./src/types", "./node_modules/@types"]
  }
}
```

Best practice: start with a minimal declaration (`declare module 'x'`) to unblock yourself, then gradually add types as you use more of the API. You can also contribute types back to DefinitelyTyped.

```
MaxListenersExceededWarning: Possible EventEmitter memory leak detected.
11 'data' listeners added to [Socket]. Use emitter.setMaxListeners() to increase limit.
```

This warning fires when more than 10 listeners are added to a single event. Usually indicates a real leak.

```typescript
import { EventEmitter } from 'node:events';

// CAUSE: Adding listeners in a loop without removing them
class DataProcessor {
  constructor(private stream: NodeJS.ReadableStream) {}

  // BAD: called multiple times, each adds a listener
  process() {
    this.stream.on('data', (chunk) => { /* never removed */ });
  }
}

// FIX 1: Use once() for one-time listeners
this.stream.once('data', handler);

// FIX 2: Remove listeners when done
const handler = (chunk: Buffer) => { /* ... */ };
this.stream.on('data', handler);
// Later:
this.stream.off('data', handler);

// FIX 3: AbortSignal for automatic cleanup (Node 20+)
const ac = new AbortController();
emitter.on('data', handler, { signal: ac.signal });
// To remove all listeners added with this signal:
ac.abort();

// FIX 4: If legitimately need many listeners
emitter.setMaxListeners(50); // Per-emitter
EventEmitter.defaultMaxListeners = 50; // Global (avoid)

// DEBUGGING: Find what's adding listeners
process.on('warning', (warning) => {
  if (warning.name === 'MaxListenersExceededWarning') {
    console.trace('Listener leak:', warning.message);
  }
});
```

TypeScript 5.0 introduced `verbatimModuleSyntax` to replace the confusing trio of `importsNotUsedAsValues`, `preserveValueImports`, and `isolatedModules`.

```jsonc
// OLD (deprecated):
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "importsNotUsedAsValues": "error",
    "preserveValueImports": true,
    "isolatedModules": true
  }
}

// NEW (TypeScript 5.0+):
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "verbatimModuleSyntax": true
  }
}
```

```typescript
// With verbatimModuleSyntax: true

// Type-only imports MUST use 'import type'
import type { User } from './types';     // OK — erased
import { User } from './types';          // Error if User is only a type

// Mixed imports use inline type
import { createUser, type User } from './users'; // OK

// Re-exports must also be explicit
export type { User } from './types';     // OK — type-only
export { User } from './types';          // Error if User is type

// Side-effect imports unchanged
import './polyfills'; // OK
```

Benefit: forces you to be explicit about what's a type vs value import. This makes output predictable for any transpiler (esbuild, swc, Babel) since they can safely drop `import type` without understanding TypeScript semantics.

Different signals and errors need different handling strategies. Getting this wrong causes silent failures or data corruption.

```typescript
// SIGTERM: graceful shutdown request (Docker, K8s, systemd)
process.on('SIGTERM', async () => {
  console.log('SIGTERM received');
  await server.close();
  await db.end();
  process.exit(0);
});

// SIGINT: Ctrl+C
process.on('SIGINT', async () => {
  console.log('SIGINT received');
  await cleanup();
  process.exit(0);
});

// Uncaught exception: BUG — process state is corrupted
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error('UNCAUGHT EXCEPTION — process must exit:', err);
  // Log to error tracking synchronously
  // DO NOT try to resume — state is unreliable
  process.exit(1);
});

// Unhandled rejection: async bug
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => {
  console.error('UNHANDLED REJECTION:', reason);
  // Since Node 15, this crashes by default
  // In older versions, add: process.exit(1);
});

// SIGUSR2: often used for diagnostics
process.on('SIGUSR2', () => {
  const v8 = require('node:v8');
  v8.writeHeapSnapshot();
  console.log('Heap snapshot written');
});

// WARNING: SIGKILL cannot be caught — it kills immediately
// Ensure SIGTERM handler completes within Docker's stop timeout (default 10s)
```

The `infer` keyword declares a type variable inside a conditional type, enabling extraction of types from complex structures.

```typescript
// Extract function parameters
type FirstParam<F> = F extends (first: infer P, ...rest: any[]) => any ? P : never;
type A = FirstParam<(name: string, age: number) => void>; // string

// Extract promise resolution type (recursive)
type Awaited<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? Awaited<U> : T;
type B = Awaited<Promise<Promise<number>>>; // number

// Extract array element type at specific index
type Head<T extends any[]> = T extends [infer First, ...any[]] ? First : never;
type Tail<T extends any[]> = T extends [any, ...infer Rest] ? Rest : never;
type C = Head<[string, number, boolean]>; // string
type D = Tail<[string, number, boolean]>; // [number, boolean]

// Extract template literal parts
type ParseRoute<T> = T extends `${infer Start}:${infer Param}/${infer Rest}`
  ? { param: Param } & ParseRoute<Rest>
  : T extends `${infer Start}:${infer Param}`
    ? { param: Param }
    : {};

// Infer from constructor
type InstanceOf<T> = T extends new (...args: any[]) => infer I ? I : never;
class MyService { name = 'test'; }
type E = InstanceOf<typeof MyService>; // MyService

// Named tuple element extraction
type EventArgs<T> = T extends (...args: infer A extends [name: string, ...data: any[]]) => void
  ? A : never;
```

TypeScript checks for extra properties ONLY when you directly assign an object literal. Assigning via a variable bypasses this check.

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

// CAUGHT: Object literal directly assigned
const user1: User = {
  name: 'Alice',
  email: 'alice@test.com',
  age: 30, // Error: 'age' does not exist in type 'User'
};

// NOT CAUGHT: Assigned via variable
const data = { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@test.com', age: 30 };
const user2: User = data; // No error! Extra 'age' is silently allowed.

// NOT CAUGHT: Returned from function
function getUser(): User {
  const u = { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@test.com', age: 30 };
  return u; // No error!
}

// NOT CAUGHT: Spread
const extra = { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@test.com', age: 30 };
const user3: User = { ...extra }; // No error!

// This matters for API responses:
async function handler(req, res) {
  const dbUser = await db.users.findOne(id); // Has password_hash, etc.
  res.json(dbUser as User); // Leaks password_hash to client!

  // FIX: Explicitly pick fields
  const { name, email } = dbUser;
  res.json({ name, email });
}
```

This is by design (structural typing), not a bug. Use `satisfies` to get excess property checking on intermediate variables.

Async generators compose naturally with `stream.pipeline()` for extract-transform-load workflows. Each generator becomes a pipeline stage.

```typescript
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';
import { createInterface } from 'node:readline';

// Stage 1: Extract — read CSV lines
async function* readLines(source: NodeJS.ReadableStream) {
  const rl = createInterface({ input: source, crlfDelay: Infinity });
  let isHeader = true;
  for await (const line of rl) {
    if (isHeader) { isHeader = false; continue; }
    yield line;
  }
}

// Stage 2: Transform — parse and filter
async function* parseAndFilter(lines: AsyncIterable<string>) {
  for await (const line of lines) {
    const [id, name, score] = line.split(',');
    const record = { id, name, score: Number(score) };
    if (record.score >= 80) yield record;
  }
}

// Stage 3: Load — format as JSON lines
async function* toJsonLines(records: AsyncIterable<any>) {
  for await (const record of records) {
    yield JSON.stringify(record) + '\n';
  }
}

// Compose the pipeline
await pipeline(
  createReadStream('students.csv'),
  readLines,
  parseAndFilter,
  toJsonLines,
  createWriteStream('high-scorers.jsonl')
);
```

Each generator processes one item at a time — constant memory regardless of file size. Pipeline handles backpressure between stages automatically. This pattern replaces heavyweight ETL frameworks for many use cases.
